In .NET MAUI, you configure lifecycle events in `CreateMauiApp()` via `ConfigureLifecycleEvents`:

```csharp
using Microsoft.Maui.LifecycleEvents;

public static MauiApp CreateMauiApp()
{
    var builder = MauiApp.CreateBuilder();
    builder.UseMauiApp<App>();

    builder.ConfigureLifecycleEvents(events =>
    {
#if ANDROID
        events.AddAndroid(android => android
            .OnPause(activity => HandleBackground())
            .OnStop(activity => HandleBackground()));
#elif IOS
        events.AddiOS(ios => ios
            .DidEnterBackground(app => HandleBackground()));
#endif
    });

    return builder.Build();
}

static void HandleBackground()
{
    // your background logic here
}
```

**Key points:**

- **`ConfigureLifecycleEvents`** is the central hook — it gives you per-platform builders (`AddAndroid`, `AddiOS`, `AddWindows`, etc.).
- Use `#if` directives to keep platform code compilable only on the target.
- Android exposes `OnPause`, `OnStop`, `OnResume`, `OnCreate`, `OnDestroy`, etc.
- iOS exposes `DidEnterBackground`, `WillEnterForeground`, `WillTerminate`, etc.

See the [official docs](https://learn.microsoft.com/dotnet/maui/fundamentals/app-lifecycle) for the full list of mappable events.
